"Winguth A., Mikolajewicz U., Gröger M., Maier-Reimer E., Schurgers G., Vizcaíno M.","Centennial-scale interactions between the carbon cycle and anthropogenic climate change using a dynamic Earth system model",2005,"Geophysical Research Letters","32","23", L23714,"1","4",,,10.1029/2005GL023681,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-31544450983&partnerID=40&md5=8402642da659774e6538e3715c59efe0","Center for Climatic Research, Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, 1225 W. Dayton St., Madison, WI 53706, United States; Max-Planck-Institut für Meteorologie, Bundesstraße 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany","Winguth, A., Center for Climatic Research, Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, 1225 W. Dayton St., Madison, WI 53706, United States; Mikolajewicz, U., Max-Planck-Institut für Meteorologie, Bundesstraße 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Gröger, M., Max-Planck-Institut für Meteorologie, Bundesstraße 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Maier-Reimer, E., Max-Planck-Institut für Meteorologie, Bundesstraße 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Schurgers, G., Max-Planck-Institut für Meteorologie, Bundesstraße 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Vizcaíno, M., Max-Planck-Institut für Meteorologie, Bundesstraße 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany","A complex Earth system model including atmosphere, ocean, ice sheets, marine carbon cycle and terrestrial vegetation was used to study the long-term response (100-1000 yrs) of the climate to different increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations. A 3.2 K global mean surface temperature increase is simulated for a 3×CO2 experiment. The freshwater input by melting of the Greenland Ice Sheet due to global warming is of minor importance compared to hydrological changes in the atmosphere. Increased equatorial upwelling enhances the tropical outgassing of CO2 from the oceans, lowering the total marine carbon uptake by 16-22%. On land, carbon release due to increase in soil temperature reduces the anthropogenic carbon uptake from CO2 fertilization up to 43%. Thus, we show that both marine and terrestrial carbon cycle have a positive feedback on climate, which has to be considered for future carbon emission scenarios. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Computer simulation; Earth (planet); Global warming; Ice; Anthropogenic climate change; Centennial scale interactions; Earth system model; Climatology; anthropogenic effect; carbon cycle; climate change; temporal variation",,,,,,"Boyle, E.A., Cadmium: Chemical tracer of deepwater paleoceanography (1988) Paleoceanography, 3, pp. 471-489; Caldeira, K., Wickett, M.E., Anthropogenic carbon and ocean pH (2003) Nature, 425, pp. 365-368; Cox, P.M., Betts, R.A., Jones, C.D., Spall, S.A., Totterdell, I.J., Acceleration of global warming due to carbon-cycle feedbacks in a coupled climate model (2000) Nature, 408, pp. 184-187; Dufresne, J.-L., Fairhead, L., Le Treut, H., Berthelot, M., Bopp, L., Ciais, P., Friedlingstein, P., Monfray, P., On the magnitude of positive feedback between future climate change and the carbon cycle (2002) Geophys. Res. Lett., 29 (10), p. 1405. , doi:10.1029/2001GL013777; Feely, R., Wanninkhof, R., Takahashi, T., Tans, P., Influence of El Nino on the equatorial Pacific contribution to atmospheric CO2 (1999) Nature, 98, pp. 597-601; Friedlingstein, P., Dufresne, J.-L., Cox, P.M., Rayner, P., How positive is the feedback between climate change and the carbon cycle (2003) Tellus, 55, pp. 692-700. , Ser. B; Gent, P.R., Willebrand, J., McDougall, T., McWilliams, J.C., Parameterizing eddy-induced tracer transport in the ocean circulation models (1995) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 25, pp. 463-474; Govindasamy, B., Thompson, S., Mirin, A., Friedlingstein, P., Wickett, M., Caldeira, K., Delire, C., Increase of carbon cycle feedback with climate sensitivity: Results from a coupled and carbon climate and carbon cycle model (2005) Tellus, 57, pp. 153-163. , Ser B; Greve, R., Application of a polythermal three dimensional ice sheet model to the Greenland Ice Sheet: Response to steady-state and transient climate scenarios (1997) J. Clim., 10, pp. 901-918; Heinze, C., Simulating oceanic CaCO3 export production in the greenhouse (2004) Geophys. Res. Lett., 31. , L16308, doi:10.1029/2004GL020613; (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis: Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, p. 881. , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) edited by J. T. Houghton et al., Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Jickells, T.D., Global iron connections between desert dust, ocean biogeochemistry, and climate (2005) Science, 308, pp. 67-71; Maier-Reimer, E., Geochemical cycles in an ocean general circulation model: Preindustrial tracer distributions (1993) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 7, pp. 645-677; Mikolajewicz, U., Voss, R., The role of the individual air-sea flux components in CO2-induced changes of the ocean's circulation and climate (2000) Clim. Dyn., 16, pp. 627-642; Riebesell, U., Zondervan, I., Tortell, P.D., Zeebe, R., Morel, F.M.M., Reduced calcification of marine plankton in response to increased atmospheric CO2 (2000) Nature, 407, pp. 364-367; Sabine, C.L., The oceanic sink for anthropogenic CO2 (2004) Science, 305, pp. 367-371; Sarmiento, J.L., Gruber, N., Brzezinski, M.A., Dunne, J.P., High-latitude controls of thermocline nutrients and low latitude biological productivity (2004) Nature, 427, pp. 56-60; Sausen, R., Voss, R., Techniques for asynchronous and periodically synchronous coupling of atmosphere and ocean models. Part I: Impact of variability (1996) Clim. Dyn., 12, pp. 605-614; Sitch, S., Evaluation of ecosystem dynamics, plant geography and terrestrial carbon cycling in the LPJ Dynamic Global Vegetation Model (2003) Global Change Biol., 9, pp. 161-185; Visbeck, M., Marshall, J., Haine, T., Spall, M., Specification of eddy transfer coefficients in coarse resolution ocean cir